## Handoff & Technical Status Report
### What Succeeded
The extraction successfully isolated the precise mechanism of Confucian extension (*tui*) from Mohist functional impartiality (*jiān'ài*). These two concepts possess deeply robust, peer-reviewed, explicitly argued definitions across English-language sinological scholarship.
### What Failed
Attempts to isolate a distinct, standalone operational definition for Daoist love-concepts within classical scholarship yielded insufficient explicit data. While concepts like *cidian* (compassion/deep love) occur in the *Daodejing*, peer-reviewed philosophical analysis frequently classifies these as reactions to or sub-variants of political cosmology rather than standalone structural frameworks of human relational love analogous to *rén* or *jiān'ài*. They were omitted to strictly preserve G4 rigidity.
### Unverified Sources
We sought but could not verify access to specific comparative chapters within *The Oxford Handbook of Chinese Philosophy* regarding late imperial transformations of *rén*, restricting this sheet strictly to the classical/early foundational layers.
### Notes for the Next Extractor/Reviewer
Pay close attention to the mechanism field when aligning this matrix with Western or South Asian traditions. The Confucian mechanism relies entirely on a developmental psychology paradigm (family as a moral incubator), whereas the Mohist mechanism relies on an external normative framework (Heaven's intent / societal utility). Do not let future synthesis steps conflate *jiān'ài* with Western *agapē*; *agapē* often flows down from a divine source as an unearned gift, whereas *jiān'ài* operates horizontally as a strictly logical system of reciprocal societal survival.
